@incollection{Day2005,
abstract = {This chapter describes various theoretical developments in the area of ecological and evolutionary processes, organizing and presenting them in a fashion that is chronological and is meant to illustrate the connections, similarities, and differences among them. Some background on theoretical ecology and theoretical evolutionary biology as independent fields of study is presented, and some examples that will illustrate various approaches have been introduced. There are many processes and types of interactions between organisms that have been the focus of ecological theory. A few of the most important include competition for resources, predation, parasitism, mutualism, and facilitation. Most recent techniques and approaches in theoretical evolutionary ecology do not represent a fundamental change in the way scientists are thinking about and modeling ecological-evolutionary feedbacks. Rather than being a paradigm shift, it represents "normal" science. What it truly fascinating, however, is that the work on single-locus models, quantitative-genetic models, game-theoretic models, and adaptive-dynamic models that have proceeded largely independent of one another, but have led to what is fundamentally the same mathematical description of evolutionary change. This suggests that there is something fundamental and robust being described by the different approaches because they have all converged on similar answers from different starting points. {\textcopyright} 2005 Copyright {\textcopyright} 2005 Elsevier Inc. All rights reserved.},
